05421nam a22008295i 9789048551125DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485511257 a10.1515/97890485511252doi  a(DE-B1597)623986  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aBH301.L3bG73 2022 7aART0150902bisacsh04a111/.85223/eng/202205231 aGrant, Katrina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLandscape and the Arts in Early Modern Italy :bTheatre, Gardens and Visual Culture /cKatrina Grant. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (292 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aVisual and Material Culture, 1300 –1700 ;v3300tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- t1. Theatricality, a View from the Landscape -- t2. Gardens of the Gods : Classical Revival, Intermedi, Early Opera and the Idea of Nature -- t3. The (Singing) Figure in the Landscape -- t4. Triumph over Nature : Machines and Meraviglia on the Seventeenth-century Stage -- t5. The Theatre in the Landscape : Pliny to Pratolino -- t6. The Garden as Stage, the Visitor as Performer -- t7. Stages without Actors : Theatres of Sculpture, Water and Flowers -- t8. Performing in the Parrhasian Grove : Green Theatres and the Academies -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book argues that theatre, and the new genre of opera in particular, played a key role in creating a new vision of landscape during the long seventeenth century in Italy. It explores how the idea of gardens as theatres emerged at the same time as opera was developed in Italian courts around the turn of the seventeenth century. During this period landscape painting emerged as a genre and the aesthetic of designed landscapes and gardens was wholly transformed, which resulted in a reconceptualization of the relationship between humans and landscape. The importance of theatre as a key cultural expression Italy is widely recognised, but the visual culture of theatre and its relationship to the broader artistic culture is still being untangled. This book argues that the combination of narratives playing out in natural settings (Arcadia, Parnassus, Alcina), the emotional responses elicited by sets and special effects (the apparent magical manipulation of the laws of nature), and, the way that garden theatres were used for displays of power and to enact princely virtue and social order, all contributed to this shifting idea of landscape in the seventeenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLandscape paintingzItalyy17th century. 0aLandscapeszItalyy17th century. 0aOperaxHistoryy17th century. 0aTheaterzItalyxHistoryy17th century. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 7aART / History / Baroque & Rococo.2bisacsh  aSet design, Landscape, Theatre, Visual Culture, Spectacle.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076709408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2022 Part 2z978311076700108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2022z9783110992809oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2022 Englishz978311099281608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048551125?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048551